<subSubSection lastPageId="115" lastPageNumber="511" pageId="114" pageNumber="510" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="114.[1427,2636,2823,3477]" pageId="114" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1428,1779,3405,3438]" pageId="114" pageNumber="510">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. Although Bailey’s White-toothed Shrew has a relatively small distribution, it is common where
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="115.[109,1315,291,525]" pageId="115" pageNumber="511">it is found, comprising a sizeable percentage (9:8-10-1%) of the small mammals captured in the Simien Mountains in 1998. However,it may be threatened by small-holder farming of crops and livestock, as well as the limited habitat destruction that has occurred in parts ofits distribution.It is found in the Simien Mountains National Park.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
